WEBVTT

00:09.469 --> 00:11.300
[Walt]
Thanks for coming, everybody.

00:11.512 --> 00:13.503
I really appreciate your time.

00:16.392 --> 00:19.509
So, what did you think
of the book?

00:20.354 --> 00:21.810
"Of Mice and Men,"

00:22.023 --> 00:23.559
it's Nobel Prize winner
John Steinbeck's

00:23.774 --> 00:25.184
classic American novel.

00:25.401 --> 00:28.814
It was published in 1937
to wide critical acclaim.

00:29.030 --> 00:30.645
Thank you, Monte.

00:30.990 --> 00:32.275
But I was hoping
to get people's, uh,

00:32.492 --> 00:34.357
personal reactions
to the book, so...

00:34.577 --> 00:36.067
[Shelby]
I hated it.

00:37.330 --> 00:40.447
It was too sad,
and everybody was so mean.

00:40.666 --> 00:42.281
Okay, um...

00:42.502 --> 00:43.912
[clears throat]

00:46.839 --> 00:48.625
Zachary, how about you?

00:48.841 --> 00:50.342
Uh...

00:50.551 --> 00:53.964
Uh, sorry, I'm a slow reader,
so I didn't finish.

00:56.307 --> 00:57.843
[door opens]

00:58.059 --> 00:59.595
-[Ruby] Hey.
-[Ferg] Hey.

00:59.810 --> 01:00.799
[door closes]

01:03.564 --> 01:04.519
-Ru by.
-[Ruby] Hm?

01:04.732 --> 01:06.097
What's Cady doing here?

01:08.027 --> 01:10.188
-Why don't you ask her yourself?
-Hey. Shh.

01:10.404 --> 01:12.611
I'm helping
with the deputy search.

01:12.823 --> 01:14.199
-[Ferg] Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

01:14.408 --> 01:15.739
My dad hired me
to do some background checks

01:15.952 --> 01:18.238
on the people he's interviewing
in there.

01:22.625 --> 01:25.708
Are they in there right now?
[clears throat] Vic.

01:25.920 --> 01:28.878
-They all in there right now?
-Yeah, all eight of them.

01:34.554 --> 01:36.215
Did you meet them yet?
[groans]

01:36.430 --> 01:37.510
Vic.

01:38.724 --> 01:41.261
Did you meet them yet?
I mean, did they seem all right?

01:41.477 --> 01:43.763
It doesn't really matter
what I think, you know?

01:43.980 --> 01:46.016
Walt's gonna hire
whoever he wants anyway,

01:46.232 --> 01:47.847
probably someone
that doesn't threaten him.

01:48.067 --> 01:49.648
lam hungry.

01:49.860 --> 01:53.444
I'm gonna go to the Busy Bee
and get some food.

01:53.656 --> 01:54.771
Anyone else want anything?

01:54.991 --> 01:57.573
[Ruby]
Mnh-mnh. Thanks.

02:01.372 --> 02:03.112
Let's focus
on the end of the book,

02:03.332 --> 02:04.742
where George shoots Lennie.

02:04.959 --> 02:07.120
Spoiler alert for Zachary, huh?

02:07.837 --> 02:09.828
Well, I'll say the big maroon
had it coming.

02:10.047 --> 02:11.753
By the time I got to the end,

02:11.966 --> 02:14.173
l was so sick
of John Malkovich's voice

02:14.385 --> 02:17.377
that l was actually rooting
for him to get shot.

02:20.308 --> 02:22.264
[clears throat]

02:22.476 --> 02:23.977
What?

02:24.186 --> 02:27.178
John Malkovich played
the character in the movie.

02:27.398 --> 02:28.979
We're talking about the book,
so...

02:29.191 --> 02:30.522
[scoffs]
Of course.

02:31.235 --> 02:34.068
Okay, uh... as a deputy,

02:34.280 --> 02:37.272
how would you handle this
George/Lennie situation?

02:37.491 --> 02:39.231
Well, at the academy,
l was trained

02:39.452 --> 02:41.158
to take cover
at a safe distance.

02:41.370 --> 02:43.747
Ideally, l'd create a barrier
between myself and the shooter.

02:43.956 --> 02:45.696
I would command him to drop
his weapon.

02:45.916 --> 02:47.247
[knock on door]

02:48.336 --> 02:51.248
Walt, sorry,
we've got a situation.

02:54.091 --> 02:55.251
[Walt]
Excuse me.

03:00.681 --> 03:02.091
There's been a shooting

03:02.308 --> 03:04.264
at the home
of Brandi and Greg Collette.

03:04.977 --> 03:06.217
[Ferg]
The Collettes?

03:07.104 --> 03:08.560
Aren't they the military family

03:08.773 --> 03:10.434
that you and Vic
got called in on a while back?

03:10.650 --> 03:14.643
Yeah, Brandi Collette had a PTSD
episode, fired a weapon at us.

03:14.862 --> 03:16.853
Thankfully, Greg had it loaded
with blanks, so...

03:17.073 --> 03:19.029
Not this time.
Greg's been shot.

03:20.034 --> 03:22.195
-By Brandi?
-I don't know.

03:26.666 --> 03:28.907
Actually, Ferg, you stay here.

03:29.126 --> 03:31.082
Tell the applicants
I'm sorry to out things short.

03:31.295 --> 03:33.456
I'll see them
at the shooting range.

03:38.302 --> 03:39.508
How is he?

03:39.762 --> 03:41.423
Bullet passed underneath
his left clavicle.

03:41.639 --> 03:42.879
He's lost a lot of blood,

03:43.099 --> 03:44.714
but all things considered,
he's a lucky guy.

03:44.934 --> 03:45.969
Where's his wife, Brandi?

03:46.185 --> 03:47.345
Didn't know he had a wife.

03:47.812 --> 03:49.768
-Sheriff, we got to go.
-l'm coming with you.

03:49.980 --> 03:51.481
[monitor beeping]

03:51.691 --> 03:53.977
[siren wailing]

03:56.112 --> 03:58.228
[radio chatter]

04:01.784 --> 04:03.445
Greg, did Brandi do this?

04:05.496 --> 04:07.361
No, she didn't.

04:07.581 --> 04:10.493
Okay, if it wasn't Brandi,
who was it?

04:11.961 --> 04:14.418
Some guy kicked in my door
while I was sleeping.

04:14.630 --> 04:15.870
Did you get a look at him?

04:16.090 --> 04:17.205
Sort of. Uh...

04:17.425 --> 04:20.292
He had a, um -- a hoodie on.

04:20.511 --> 04:25.096
A red bandana covered his face.

04:25.266 --> 04:29.259
White guy, sounded young,
maybe drugged out.

04:29.478 --> 04:30.729
What did he want?

04:30.938 --> 04:32.439
I don't know, okay?

04:32.648 --> 04:34.684
I was gonna let him take
whatever he was looking for

04:34.900 --> 04:36.765
just so he would leave.

04:38.195 --> 04:41.483
And then he found Brandi's
engagement ring, and...

04:41.699 --> 04:43.530
couldn't have that.

04:43.743 --> 04:46.860
So I tried to grab it,
and he pulled out a gun.

04:47.830 --> 04:49.491
I didn't care.
| just -- I went after it.

04:49.707 --> 04:54.121
Then he shot me, and then he
ran away with the ring.

04:54.336 --> 04:56.076
So, where was Brandi
during all this?

04:56.297 --> 04:57.537
She okay?

05:00.009 --> 05:01.545
She's dead, Sheriff.

05:03.179 --> 05:05.215
She killed herself
two months ago.

05:06.182 --> 05:07.797
I had no idea.

05:09.769 --> 05:11.009
I'm sorry.

05:20.237 --> 05:21.568
You, uh...

05:23.073 --> 05:25.109
Can you describe
that engagement ring for me?

05:26.786 --> 05:28.822
Green agate, set in silver.

05:30.372 --> 05:31.623
Brandi found the stone

05:31.832 --> 05:33.788
while we were camping
near Delaney Rim.

05:35.878 --> 05:37.368
[exhales sharply]
It's got her name.

05:37.588 --> 05:39.499
It's engraved on the inside.

05:42.259 --> 05:45.467
I'm gonna find
that ring for you, Greg...

05:45.679 --> 05:47.465
and whoever did this.

05:47.681 --> 05:50.263
Sheriff, I think
you're gonna want to hear this.

05:50.476 --> 05:51.807
[Vic]
A second robbery?

05:52.019 --> 05:53.759
[Ruby]
Yeah, at the TaII-T Warehouse

05:53.979 --> 05:55.059
and another gunshot victim.

05:55.272 --> 05:56.523
Hand me that mike.

06:00.694 --> 06:02.400
Vic, where are you?

06:02.613 --> 06:05.025
[siren wailing]

06:06.700 --> 06:08.691
[tires screech]

06:09.954 --> 06:12.240
Have the doctor call me
as soon as he's out of surgery.

06:12.456 --> 06:14.572
[siren beeps, wails]

06:28.389 --> 06:31.131
[siren wailing]

06:41.485 --> 06:43.191
Who called this one in?

06:43.487 --> 06:45.899
The victim, a security guard
named Lee McKinnon.

07:02.006 --> 07:03.587
Sheriff's department!

07:03.757 --> 07:05.372
[Lee]
I'm over here!

07:12.516 --> 07:13.631
They got me in the leg.

07:14.351 --> 07:16.091
They? How many?

07:16.312 --> 07:18.303
Three, I think, maybe four.

07:18.522 --> 07:19.807
They're gone now.

07:21.400 --> 07:23.231
l was going around
checking temps,

07:23.444 --> 07:25.230
and that's when
I heard something.

07:25.446 --> 07:28.438
And I came around the corner
here, and I saw them.

07:28.657 --> 07:29.863
[Walt]
What did they look like?

07:30.367 --> 07:31.698
They were all in black,

07:31.911 --> 07:33.947
ski masks, looked professional.

07:34.163 --> 07:36.654
Sol pulled my sidearm,
and before I knew it,

07:36.874 --> 07:38.614
we were exchanging shots.

07:39.460 --> 07:41.542
[Vic]
Did you hit any of them?

07:41.754 --> 07:43.915
I sure as hell would hope so.
They were all right there.

07:44.131 --> 07:46.838
They were taking boxes
off our Casper shipment.

07:47.051 --> 07:48.416
[Walt]
These all pharmaceuticals?

07:48.636 --> 07:50.217
Yeah.

07:50.429 --> 07:53.387
If you see any painkillers,
you can grab me some.

07:53.599 --> 07:55.135
Paramedics are on their way.

07:55.351 --> 07:57.512
-[Lee] Aah!
-[Walt] How's that leg looking?

07:59.063 --> 08:00.553
You stitch that yourself?

08:01.482 --> 08:04.895
Aah.
Uh, no, one of them did it.

08:06.070 --> 08:07.981
[inhales sharply]

08:08.197 --> 08:09.858
[shudders]

08:15.579 --> 08:17.695
[siren wails]

08:18.749 --> 08:20.614
Two armed robberies in one day?

08:20.834 --> 08:23.416
They got to be connected.
-[Walt] Maybe.

08:23.629 --> 08:25.745
Lee McKinnon shot those robbers
at close range.

08:25.965 --> 08:27.796
Call the hospitals
and the local clinics.

08:28.008 --> 08:30.215
See if any gunshot victims
have shown up.

08:30.427 --> 08:32.418
Have Ruby call every pawnshop
in the area.

08:32.638 --> 08:34.970
See if anyone brought in
a green agate engagement ring

08:35.182 --> 08:36.342
set in silver.

08:36.558 --> 08:37.934
You looking to propose
to someone?

08:38.143 --> 08:41.101
It was, uh,
Brandi Collette's ring.

08:41.313 --> 08:42.644
Greg got shot trying to stop

08:42.856 --> 08:43.845
someone stealing it, so...

08:44.233 --> 08:45.222
Green agate must be worth

08:45.442 --> 08:47.057
a lot more than I suspected.

08:47.277 --> 08:49.359
Brandi killed herself
two months ago.

08:50.322 --> 08:54.065
Shit. Okay.
I'll call Ruby from the road.

08:54.785 --> 08:57.447
Ferg, I want you to thoroughly
process these crime scenes,

08:57.663 --> 08:59.244
this place
and the Collette home.

08:59.999 --> 09:02.285
Tell me the differences
and the similarities.

09:03.377 --> 09:05.914
That should tell us if these
two robberies are connected.

09:16.348 --> 09:18.134
Ferg.

09:18.350 --> 09:19.760
Call Cady for me.

09:19.977 --> 09:21.262
On it.

09:21.937 --> 09:24.349
-Why?
-I need a ride.

09:33.949 --> 09:35.530
Yeah, that's right.

09:37.202 --> 09:39.284
ls Greg Collette out of surgery?

09:41.040 --> 09:43.372
Anybody there to be with him
when he comes 'round?

09:44.918 --> 09:46.749
When are the visiting hours?

09:47.796 --> 09:49.411
Okay, thanks.

09:49.631 --> 09:50.495
[beep]

09:50.716 --> 09:52.047
So, uh...

09:53.260 --> 09:55.421
You dig up anything
on these candidates

09:55.596 --> 09:56.711
I ought to know about?

09:56.930 --> 09:58.386
Dad, do you feel like

09:58.599 --> 10:01.341
maybe you're rushing
this a little?

10:01.560 --> 10:03.175
You've been through a lot.

10:03.395 --> 10:05.260
Thanks, but I'm good.

10:05.481 --> 10:07.017
Now, what have you found?

10:08.734 --> 10:11.817
Well, two of your applicants
have minor criminal records,

10:12.029 --> 10:13.690
and one of them
has a medical history

10:13.906 --> 10:15.191
that's a little disconcerting.

10:15.407 --> 10:16.567
Okay.

10:22.915 --> 10:27.158
Now, I hope you never need to
use your weapon on this job.

10:27.377 --> 10:31.711
But if you do,
I hope you don't miss.

10:33.467 --> 10:35.583
Treat this like the real thing.

10:36.678 --> 10:37.758
All right.

10:38.764 --> 10:39.799
Ready.

10:41.642 --> 10:43.052
Aim.

10:43.268 --> 10:44.519
Fire.

10:58.617 --> 10:59.652
Not bad, Theo.

10:59.868 --> 11:01.733
Thanks, Sheriff.

11:03.038 --> 11:07.077
Monte, | get the feeling
you may have done this before.

11:07.292 --> 11:08.247
Yes, sir.

11:18.846 --> 11:20.632
Something wrong, Zachary?

11:21.723 --> 11:24.556
You said to treat this
like the real thing, right?

11:24.768 --> 11:26.224
Well, in reality,
at this distance,

11:26.436 --> 11:27.846
that bear's no threat to me,

11:28.063 --> 11:29.223
so I prefer not to shoot it.

11:32.276 --> 11:33.857
Actually, that's not a bear.

11:34.444 --> 11:37.732
That's an escaped killer
in a bear suit.

11:37.948 --> 11:42.032
He's got an AK-47
aimed straight at you.

11:46.415 --> 11:48.326
[shell clinks]

11:51.044 --> 11:52.204
Nice shooting.

11:54.840 --> 11:56.171
[Vic]
Walt.

12:02.723 --> 12:04.964
So, if Lee McKinnon did hit
one of those warehouse robbers,

12:05.184 --> 12:06.640
they didn't go to a hospital
or clinic.

12:06.852 --> 12:08.467
Nobody's been admitted
with a gunshot wound

12:08.687 --> 12:10.928
except for McKinnon
and Greg Collette.

12:11.148 --> 12:12.604
What about Brandi's ring?

12:12.816 --> 12:14.272
Ruby's still making calls,

12:14.484 --> 12:15.644
but I just got off
the phone with Ferg.

12:15.861 --> 12:17.397
He said 12 boxes
of pharmaceuticals

12:17.613 --> 12:18.773
were stolen from the warehouse,

12:18.989 --> 12:20.354
all from the same
Casper shipment.

12:20.574 --> 12:23.657
Zoloft, Children's Advil,
and pseudo-ephedrine.

12:23.869 --> 12:25.405
-Pseudoephedrine.
-[Vic] Pseudoephedrine.

12:25.621 --> 12:26.861
Pseudoephedrine?

12:27.080 --> 12:28.581
Meth cooks use it.

12:28.999 --> 12:31.365
So I've been thinking,
home invasion, stolen pills,

12:31.585 --> 12:32.665
ring a bell?

12:32.878 --> 12:35.870
-Yeah. U nfortunately.
-Yeah.

12:36.089 --> 12:38.341
Cady, uh, tell the candidates

12:38.550 --> 12:40.541
that didn't check out
they didn't make the cut,

12:40.761 --> 12:42.092
except for the medical case.

12:42.304 --> 12:44.135
I'm not quite ready
to cut him loose yet.

12:44.348 --> 12:45.554
Okay.

12:55.400 --> 12:57.482
[hip-hop music playing]

13:00.239 --> 13:02.230
I'll do the talking.

13:02.449 --> 13:04.314
You head inside
and look for the missing drugs

13:04.534 --> 13:06.115
and Brandi's ring.

13:06.828 --> 13:09.911
[Vic] Let's hope for their sakes
we only find drugs.

13:12.125 --> 13:13.865
-Boys.
-[music stops]

13:14.086 --> 13:16.452
Yo, bae, that's trespassing
without a warrant.

13:16.672 --> 13:19.163
You're on probation.
We don't need a warrant.

13:20.467 --> 13:22.207
You still peddling stolen drugs
these days?

13:22.427 --> 13:23.837
-You mean magazines?
-No!

13:24.054 --> 13:25.635
-Come on!
-I don't.

13:28.225 --> 13:30.591
Like you said,
we're on probation.

13:30.811 --> 13:33.678
Selling drugs would wreck
that shit. So we're clean.

13:33.897 --> 13:34.932
Who's taken over
your drug trade?

13:35.148 --> 13:36.399
No one.

13:36.608 --> 13:37.518
You've completely cleaned up

13:37.734 --> 13:39.599
Absaroka County, Sheriff.

13:39.820 --> 13:44.689
And yet someone just robbed
a warehouse at gunpoint,

13:44.908 --> 13:48.071
stole entire cases
of pseudoephedrine, Zoloft,

13:48.287 --> 13:50.243
and Children's Advil.

13:50.455 --> 13:52.241
And someone ripped offjewelry

13:52.457 --> 13:54.197
from a grieving widower
after shooting him.

13:54.418 --> 13:56.249
I'm thinking the two of you

13:56.461 --> 13:57.997
are about stupid enough
to do both.

13:58.797 --> 14:01.209
Look what I just found
under one of the couch cushions.

14:01.425 --> 14:02.961
[chuckles]

14:03.176 --> 14:05.087
Well, that's a violation
of your probation,

14:05.304 --> 14:09.843
which mean I'm calling
your probation officer right now

14:10.058 --> 14:11.559
unless I believe
every single word

14:11.768 --> 14:12.883
that comes out of your mouths.

14:13.103 --> 14:14.468
We're not lying.

14:14.855 --> 14:16.015
Our proby's a hard-ass.

14:16.231 --> 14:18.392
We wouldn't risk
peddling Z-Ioft.

14:18.608 --> 14:19.893
What about the pseudoephedrine?

14:20.110 --> 14:21.441
There's no money is pseudo,

14:21.653 --> 14:22.642
not unless you cook
that shit up.

14:22.863 --> 14:24.444
And what if you can?

14:24.656 --> 14:26.157
[sighs]

14:26.366 --> 14:29.153
You can flip a package of pseudo
for three grams of meth,

14:29.369 --> 14:30.449
maybe sell it for 100 bucks

14:30.662 --> 14:32.118
to some dumb-ass
casino tourists.

14:32.331 --> 14:34.322
But we don't know how to cook
that redneck shit.

14:34.541 --> 14:35.621
No.

14:43.300 --> 14:45.256
And, Sheriff?

14:47.012 --> 14:49.674
That's actually my nana's gun.

14:49.890 --> 14:52.051
[Walt]
Your nana's gun?

14:52.267 --> 14:56.431
You tell your nana to come down
to the station and pick it up.

15:12.996 --> 15:15.612
So, those idiots are right
about meth's street --

15:15.832 --> 15:18.118
-Hey.
-...street value.

15:18.335 --> 15:20.496
Each one of those cases
of pseudoephedrine

15:20.712 --> 15:23.203
could be worth
tens of thousands of dollars.

15:24.383 --> 15:25.873
What did you find
at the crime scenes?

15:26.093 --> 15:27.754
Found some slugs
at the warehouse

15:27.969 --> 15:29.095
and at Greg Collette's home.

15:29.262 --> 15:30.172
I figure
we should run ballistics

15:30.389 --> 15:31.799
on all of them.

15:32.015 --> 15:34.222
Even though the robbery
at the Collette home

15:34.434 --> 15:36.095
looks like a random
smash-and-grab,

15:36.311 --> 15:38.472
I decided to make some calls
on Greg Collette anyway,

15:38.688 --> 15:40.770
see if he has any enemies
or any recent run-ins.

15:40.982 --> 15:42.233
Is that why you
brought Travis in?

15:42.442 --> 15:44.728
Uh... no.

15:44.945 --> 15:47.561
Uh... he brought himself in.

15:47.781 --> 15:49.442
Said he wanted to talk
to you in private.

15:49.658 --> 15:50.738
I have no idea what about.

15:50.951 --> 15:52.066
Anyway, Greg Collette

15:52.285 --> 15:53.661
did have a big blowup

15:53.870 --> 15:55.121
at the VA. clinic in Sheridan

15:55.330 --> 15:57.491
directed at a psychiatrist --

15:57.707 --> 16:00.039
Dr. Donna Sue Monaghan.

16:00.252 --> 16:01.617
Nice work.

16:02.754 --> 16:04.164
Travis.

16:04.965 --> 16:06.626
Uh... hi.

16:06.842 --> 16:08.833
-What are you doing here?
-I'm honored to apply

16:09.052 --> 16:10.337
for the job of deputy, sir.

16:10.554 --> 16:12.090
I-I know me and this department

16:12.305 --> 16:13.636
may have gotten off
on the wrong foot,

16:13.849 --> 16:15.009
but I really do believe

16:15.225 --> 16:16.055
that I'd make
a strong candidate.

16:16.268 --> 16:17.553
Aside from pulling a gun

16:17.769 --> 16:18.849
on one of my deputies

16:19.062 --> 16:20.438
and later helping him kidnap

16:20.647 --> 16:22.433
and drug a Cheyenne man.

16:22.649 --> 16:24.560
Well, to be fair,
I did come clean on both

16:24.776 --> 16:26.061
of those errors in judgment.

16:26.278 --> 16:27.984
So I do have honesty
going for me.

16:28.196 --> 16:31.279
Also, I've, uh, attached
this article.

16:31.491 --> 16:34.107
It says that a lot of cops
would have become criminals

16:34.327 --> 16:36.067
if they hadn't turned
to law enforcement.

16:36.288 --> 16:37.573
So, you're saying
if I don't hire you,

16:37.789 --> 16:39.029
you're gonna commit more crimes.

16:39.249 --> 16:41.831
[laughs]
Not any felonies.

16:42.043 --> 16:43.419
As you can see, I, uh --

16:43.628 --> 16:45.004
I've never done
any real jail time,

16:45.213 --> 16:46.202
and I've never been convicted
of anything

16:46.423 --> 16:47.663
other than the misdemeanor.

16:49.926 --> 16:53.635
You actually stapled
your rap sheet to your résumé?

16:53.847 --> 16:55.963
My greatest weakness happens
to be my greatest strength.

16:56.183 --> 16:57.548
I know where the bad guys are.

16:57.767 --> 17:00.509
I know how they think,
and I'm a quick draw.

17:00.729 --> 17:01.889
[chuckles]

17:02.105 --> 17:03.970
[pen clicks]

17:04.191 --> 17:05.271
Uh...

17:06.026 --> 17:08.017
I'm in the middle
of an investigation, so...

17:08.236 --> 17:11.319
-All right.
-I'm gonna drive to Sheridan,

17:11.531 --> 17:12.771
talk to that psychiatrist

17:12.991 --> 17:14.902
that Greg Collette
had the run-in with.

17:16.453 --> 17:19.866
Uh, I want you to see
if anyone's buying or stealing

17:20.081 --> 17:22.572
the other ingredients you need
to cook meth in bulk.

17:22.792 --> 17:23.918
Okay.

17:32.427 --> 17:35.635
Well, I think that went better
than expected.

17:38.433 --> 17:40.924
[indistinct conversations]

17:50.862 --> 17:52.568
[door closes]

17:52.739 --> 17:54.195
[man]
Come on.

17:56.451 --> 17:58.407
Thanks, but no thanks.

18:12.050 --> 18:13.130
Sheriff Longmire.

18:13.343 --> 18:14.458
Yeah.

18:21.851 --> 18:24.718
Dr. Monaghan,
let me help you with that.

18:24.938 --> 18:25.927
[Donna]
Oh, thank you.

18:26.106 --> 18:27.767
-What happened?
-[sighs]

18:27.983 --> 18:31.601
Well, it was either a temper
tantrum or a breakthrough.

18:31.820 --> 18:33.105
It's hard to tell sometimes.

18:33.321 --> 18:34.356
And the name is Donna.

18:34.573 --> 18:35.562
Donna. Right.

18:35.782 --> 18:36.942
Yeah.

18:38.118 --> 18:40.860
Well, I do have another patient
in about five minutes, so...

18:41.079 --> 18:42.580
Of course.
I'll get right to it.

18:42.789 --> 18:46.247
Do you know a Durant man
named Greg Collette?

18:46.459 --> 18:48.791
Yes, he reached out to me

18:49.004 --> 18:51.962
a few months ago
about his wife, Brandi.

18:52.173 --> 18:53.583
She was, uh...

18:53.800 --> 18:55.301
She was having some
pretty terrible flashbacks

18:55.510 --> 18:57.296
after coming home from Iraq.

18:57.512 --> 18:58.843
Yeah. Yeah, I experienced one
of them firsthand, so...

18:59.055 --> 19:00.636
Well, then you know that she

19:00.849 --> 19:03.431
was in need of immediate
psychiatric care.

19:03.643 --> 19:06.680
But, unfortunately,
like too many veterans,

19:06.896 --> 19:09.023
she wouldn't come in here
for treatment.

19:09.232 --> 19:10.893
So at Greg's request,

19:11.109 --> 19:13.225
I took the mobile unit
down to Durant to see her,

19:13.445 --> 19:16.733
but she refused evaluation,
so...

19:16.948 --> 19:18.279
How did Greg react to that?

19:18.491 --> 19:20.072
Well, he was thankful
for my efforts.

19:20.285 --> 19:22.071
[chuckles]
I'm sorry.

19:22.287 --> 19:25.199
Why are you asking me all these
questions about Greg Collette?

19:25.415 --> 19:28.248
Because someone broke into his
home this morning and shot him.

19:29.294 --> 19:31.376
Well, is he okay?

19:31.588 --> 19:32.998
I hope so.

19:33.590 --> 19:35.126
Anyway, I understand
that you and Greg

19:35.342 --> 19:37.207
had a bit of a confrontation.

19:38.303 --> 19:41.841
Well, I -- Yes.
[stammers]

19:43.058 --> 19:45.640
It was about three months ago.
He, uh --

19:45.852 --> 19:47.592
He drove down here and demanded

19:47.812 --> 19:50.349
that I give him some
anti-depressants for Brandi.

19:50.565 --> 19:52.066
What did you say?

19:52.275 --> 19:54.982
I said the only thing
I could say -- no.

19:55.195 --> 19:57.060
Without an evaluation,
l-l didn't know

19:57.280 --> 19:58.941
if Brandi was suffering
from PTSD

19:59.157 --> 20:01.113
or a traumatic brain injury
or both.

20:01.326 --> 20:02.987
You know,
there was no way of knowing

20:03.203 --> 20:05.068
what kind of medication
to give her, so...

20:05.288 --> 20:07.244
And did that make Greg angry?

20:07.457 --> 20:09.948
Yes, it made him very livid.

20:10.168 --> 20:14.252
He, uh, told me that if I
didn't give him the pills

20:14.464 --> 20:18.582
that, um, Brandi
would kill herself.

20:18.802 --> 20:21.134
But there was really nothing
that I could do.

20:21.346 --> 20:23.712
At that point,
my hands were tied, so...

20:23.932 --> 20:26.344
Well, Greg was right
about Brandi, you know?

20:26.559 --> 20:28.174
She did kill herself.

20:28.395 --> 20:30.511
Do you actually think
that I don't know that, Sheriff?

20:32.357 --> 20:35.190
Do you imagine that that doesn't
keep me awake at night?

20:37.070 --> 20:41.484
Did you know that 22 veterans
kill themselves every day?

20:44.327 --> 20:46.113
You know, I had no idea
when I took this job

20:46.329 --> 20:47.990
that it was gonna be
so impossible

20:48.206 --> 20:51.369
for me to give these people
the kind of help that they need.

20:53.044 --> 20:55.660
A soldier does not hesitate

20:55.880 --> 20:58.132
to get the shrapnel
removed from his leg.

20:58.341 --> 21:00.753
But if it's the brain
that's injured,

21:00.969 --> 21:03.756
you can't get them
to set foot in here.

21:05.557 --> 21:07.548
They think that it makes them
weak or something.

21:07.767 --> 21:09.098
And just...

21:09.310 --> 21:12.768
So what do they do?
They -- They suffer.

21:12.939 --> 21:14.645
And they self-medicate.

21:14.858 --> 21:16.189
And sometimes,
like Brandi Collette,

21:16.401 --> 21:17.641
they kill themselves.

21:18.862 --> 21:21.319
And if they actually do
work up the courage

21:21.531 --> 21:23.192
to come in here, well,
then they find

21:23.408 --> 21:24.864
that we are so underfunded

21:25.076 --> 21:27.818
and that the red tape
is so damn thick,

21:28.037 --> 21:29.447
it's all just starting to feel

21:29.622 --> 21:31.362
like some, you know,
sadistic joke, but...

21:34.377 --> 21:35.583
I'm sorry. Excuse me.

21:35.795 --> 21:37.831
It's okay. It's okay.
I've got it.

21:38.047 --> 21:39.378
I'm sorry.

21:42.510 --> 21:44.011
[sighs]

21:44.220 --> 21:45.426
I'm sorry.

21:45.638 --> 21:46.764
It's uh...

21:46.973 --> 21:49.134
It's been a long week.

21:49.350 --> 21:51.557
So...
[clears throat]

21:51.770 --> 21:53.101
I really do have
a lot more patients,

21:53.313 --> 21:54.428
so if you don't have
any more questions...

21:54.647 --> 21:55.602
Where were you this morning

21:55.815 --> 21:56.850
just after dawn?

21:57.066 --> 21:58.681
I was on the road

21:58.902 --> 22:00.858
back from Cumberland County
in the mobile unit.

22:01.070 --> 22:02.651
-Why?
-I'm just trying

22:02.864 --> 22:04.604
to piece together
all the information that I can.

22:07.160 --> 22:09.116
-All right.
-Thank you.

22:09.329 --> 22:10.409
[Donna]
Of course.

22:19.881 --> 22:23.840
Deputy Ferguson here
has examined two crime scenes,

22:24.052 --> 22:26.714
one victim
at the Collette home invasion,

22:26.930 --> 22:30.172
one at the Tall-T Warehouse
robbery. Ferg?

22:30.391 --> 22:32.882
All right, Greg Collette
was shot with a .38

22:33.102 --> 22:35.184
by a single robber in his home.

22:35.396 --> 22:37.933
Later that same morning,
Lee McKinnon

22:38.149 --> 22:41.141
was shot with a 9mm in his leg
while confronting a group

22:41.361 --> 22:43.522
of three to four
professional-looking thieves.

22:43.738 --> 22:46.650
Now, McKinnon returned fire
with his .38,

22:46.866 --> 22:49.733
leaving these bullet holes
in the warehouse boxes.

22:51.538 --> 22:56.328
So, you think
these crimes are related?

22:57.126 --> 22:59.208
They got to be related.

22:59.420 --> 23:01.081
This is small-town Wyoming,
right?

23:01.297 --> 23:02.673
What are the odds

23:02.882 --> 23:04.622
that there are two heist crews
working out here?

23:04.843 --> 23:07.425
Wait, you're saying
that these perps

23:07.637 --> 23:09.298
completely altered their M.O.s?

23:09.514 --> 23:11.721
Why would they suddenly change
things up between crimes?

23:11.933 --> 23:14.470
Maybe they want
to throw us off their scent.

23:14.686 --> 23:16.768
[Walt]
Zachary, what do you think?

23:16.980 --> 23:21.019
I think these two .38 slugs
are maybe from the same gun.

23:21.234 --> 23:25.193
Both got six lands and grooves
and a left twist.

23:25.405 --> 23:26.520
[Premo]
What does that mean?

23:27.657 --> 23:29.522
That means that Zachary noticed

23:29.742 --> 23:31.607
the same thing
as Deputy Ferguson.

23:31.828 --> 23:33.693
We're doing some further
ballistic tests,

23:33.913 --> 23:35.619
but there's a good chance
that Lee McKinnon's gun

23:35.832 --> 23:37.572
was used at the
Collette home invasion, so...

23:37.792 --> 23:39.498
And did you recover
McKinnon's gun?

23:39.711 --> 23:42.669
No. McKinnon told us the robbers
took it after he was shot.

23:42.881 --> 23:44.621
But Collette was shot first.

23:44.841 --> 23:47.378
How would he be shot
with the security guard's gun?

23:47.594 --> 23:49.926
[Travis]
Easy. The guard was in on it.

23:50.138 --> 23:51.594
See, the security guard,
he rips off

23:51.806 --> 23:52.921
this Collette fellow first,

23:53.099 --> 23:54.805
and then he goes to work
his shift,

23:55.018 --> 23:56.599
and then he stages
a fake robbery

23:56.811 --> 23:58.347
to make it look like
it's a crime spree.

23:58.563 --> 24:01.100
I mean, he's a security guard,
right? I hate those guys.

24:01.316 --> 24:02.977
Fake wannabe rent-a-cops.

24:03.192 --> 24:05.183
What are you doing here?

24:05.403 --> 24:06.768
Just winning you over.

24:06.988 --> 24:08.194
I mean, you never said no
yesterday.

24:08.406 --> 24:10.522
Okay, then. No.

24:10.742 --> 24:13.154
Come on, you got to
at least give me a chance.

24:13.369 --> 24:15.860
I don't.

24:17.832 --> 24:18.947
Okay.

24:24.923 --> 24:27.505
So, uh, there's another way

24:27.717 --> 24:30.834
of, uh, thinking about this.

24:31.054 --> 24:33.261
Maybe the warehouse
was robbed first

24:33.473 --> 24:35.714
before the Collette
home invasion.

24:35.934 --> 24:38.300
Warehouse thieves shoot
Lee McKinnon,

24:38.519 --> 24:40.430
steal his gun,
hit the Collette house.

24:40.647 --> 24:43.514
Well, then why did the 911 calls
come in a different order?

24:43.733 --> 24:47.692
If this security guard McKinnon
really is an inside man,

24:47.904 --> 24:49.394
after the warehouse robbery,

24:49.614 --> 24:51.980
he lets his cohorts shoot him
in the leg.

24:52.200 --> 24:54.282
Then he would have waited
to call 911

24:54.494 --> 24:55.779
to let his crew get away.

24:55.995 --> 24:57.860
Meanwhile, they use
Lee McKinnon's gun

24:58.081 --> 25:00.697
in another robbery
in another part of town.

25:00.917 --> 25:02.578
Didn't Trey and Jelly
have an inside partner

25:02.794 --> 25:04.125
in their prescription-drug ring?

25:04.337 --> 25:06.669
Yes, they did.
Paid off a pharmacist

25:06.881 --> 25:09.372
to give them the names of people
with prescriptions.

25:11.302 --> 25:13.133
All four cases
of stolen pseudoephedrine

25:13.346 --> 25:15.632
showed up in the Dumpster
behind Durant Pharmacy

25:15.848 --> 25:18.840
right after you and I
questioned Jelly and Trey.

25:19.060 --> 25:20.766
That's got to be enough
for an arrest.

25:20.979 --> 25:23.812
No. Everything we have
is still circumstantial.

25:24.023 --> 25:27.481
Unless one of our shooting
victims can give us an ID.

25:28.778 --> 25:29.938
Greg.

25:30.154 --> 25:31.610
Sheriff.

25:31.823 --> 25:33.563
Are they taking half-decent care
of you in here?

25:33.783 --> 25:35.774
Uh, no complaints so far,
you know.

25:35.994 --> 25:37.404
Uh... [clears throat]

25:37.620 --> 25:39.030
Marc, this is
Sheriff Walt Longmire,

25:39.247 --> 25:41.078
who I was telling you about.

25:41.290 --> 25:44.453
Sheriff, this is my friend
Sergeant Marc Van Zandt.

25:44.669 --> 25:46.159
Actually, it's
retired Sergeant Van Zandt.

25:46.379 --> 25:47.664
It's nice to meet you, Sheriff.

25:47.880 --> 25:49.006
Greg tells me you're
hunting down the asshole

25:49.215 --> 25:50.955
that shot him
and stole Brandi's ring.

25:51.175 --> 25:53.666
Well, I'm certainly working
on it.

25:53.886 --> 25:55.422
Did you know Brandi?

25:56.723 --> 25:58.839
[Marc]
Yes, sir. Very well.

25:59.058 --> 26:00.218
If it was anyone
other than Brandi

26:00.435 --> 26:02.471
driving our supply truck
through Basra,

26:02.687 --> 26:04.097
I don't think I'd be here.

26:04.439 --> 26:06.304
So when Greg called me
and told me about the robbery,

26:06.524 --> 26:08.139
I drove up from Fort Collins
to make sure

26:08.359 --> 26:09.690
they were taking care of him.

26:09.902 --> 26:11.278
No.

26:11.487 --> 26:13.318
We're doing everything we can,
so, uh...

26:14.323 --> 26:18.157
I got a couple of suspects
I think might be involved.

26:18.369 --> 26:19.745
Greg, if you feel up to it,

26:19.912 --> 26:22.870
you want to take a look
at their mug shots?

26:23.082 --> 26:24.117
Yeah, sure, let's...

26:24.333 --> 26:25.618
Here you go.
[clears throat]

26:27.420 --> 26:29.081
Only a mother
could love them, huh?

26:29.297 --> 26:31.834
[Greg]
[chuckles] Yeah. Yeah.

26:32.842 --> 26:35.675
You recognize either of them?

26:36.763 --> 26:38.299
I don't know.

26:38.514 --> 26:40.175
Like I said, I was sleeping
when they busted in.

26:40.391 --> 26:42.006
They had their faces covered.

26:42.226 --> 26:44.012
I wish I could, but sorry.

26:44.228 --> 26:46.435
No, no, makes sense.

26:46.606 --> 26:48.562
If you could hear
the robber's voice,

26:48.775 --> 26:51.232
you think that
may make things easier?

26:52.195 --> 26:54.311
-It might, right?
-Yeah.

26:55.031 --> 26:55.986
Okay.

26:56.199 --> 26:58.110
Hey, who you taking me to see?

26:58.910 --> 27:01.242
It's a guy named Greg Collette.

27:01.454 --> 27:04.491
He was also shot during
a robbery yesterday.

27:11.255 --> 27:14.122
[Walt] Mr. McKinnon,
thanks forjoining us.

27:14.342 --> 27:16.628
I was hoping
that you and Mr. Collette here

27:16.844 --> 27:18.300
could go through
some of the details

27:18.513 --> 27:20.879
of your assailants with us.

27:21.099 --> 27:24.432
That way, we might be able
to piece together a description.

27:24.644 --> 27:29.354
Do you recognize
either of these two men?

27:30.358 --> 27:31.973
You know, it was dark,

27:32.193 --> 27:34.400
and the fellas
kept their masks on.

27:34.612 --> 27:36.398
I don't think
I could really recognize

27:36.614 --> 27:38.525
any of the people involved.

27:40.535 --> 27:43.322
Not even the one who sewed up
your gunshot wound?

27:49.168 --> 27:52.456
How long did it take for you
to call 911 after you got shot?

27:52.672 --> 27:56.005
It's pretty hard to pin down.
Um...

27:56.217 --> 27:58.583
You know, I think I blacked out
in there somewhere.

28:00.221 --> 28:02.633
I don't even remember
being sewn up.

28:02.849 --> 28:04.680
[Marc]
Fog of war.

28:05.810 --> 28:07.300
Excuse me?

28:07.520 --> 28:08.726
Well, in a crisis, our brains

28:08.938 --> 28:10.394
can only handle so much
information.

28:10.606 --> 28:13.439
Our memory of the details
gets all fogged up.

28:13.651 --> 28:15.562
I saw it happen
all the time in Iraq.

28:24.078 --> 28:26.364
There was something weird going
on in there, wasn't there?

28:26.581 --> 28:28.117
Lee McKinnon
seemed awfully nervous

28:28.332 --> 28:30.072
around Sergeant Van Zandt.

28:31.085 --> 28:32.791
[Ferg]
Do you think he was in on it?

28:33.004 --> 28:34.289
[Wait]
I don't know.

28:35.089 --> 28:37.250
McKinnon's injury isn't severe.

28:37.466 --> 28:39.457
When's he scheduled
to be released?

28:39.677 --> 28:40.666
[Ferg]
Tomorrow.

28:40.887 --> 28:42.047
[Walt]
I got a job for you.

28:42.263 --> 28:43.719
[rock music playing]

28:53.316 --> 28:56.604
Okay, so, it had nothing to do
with his physical health?

28:56.819 --> 28:57.899
Okay.

28:58.863 --> 29:00.728
Okay, thank you so much
for your help.

29:06.245 --> 29:07.325
Big crowd.

29:07.538 --> 29:09.039
Casino overflow.

29:09.248 --> 29:12.035
Well, thank you
for covering for me.

29:12.251 --> 29:14.333
No problem.
Something come up?

29:14.545 --> 29:16.331
Just a friend in need.

29:19.217 --> 29:20.753
Has Malachi put you on retainer?

29:20.968 --> 29:22.469
Yeah, he offered me six figures.

29:22.678 --> 29:23.963
I turned him down, of course,

29:24.180 --> 29:25.590
so that I could do
some background checks

29:25.806 --> 29:27.967
on my dad's deputy applicants.

29:32.355 --> 29:33.686
Is he one of the candidates?

29:33.898 --> 29:35.354
Yeah.
Why? You know him?

29:38.444 --> 29:41.686
I have encountered
Theo Pemberton several times,

29:41.906 --> 29:44.443
and each could be described
as "harrowing."

29:44.659 --> 29:47.492
Okay, good to know.
Thank you.

29:47.703 --> 29:49.284
Your shirt's ripped.

29:53.834 --> 29:55.040
So it is.

29:57.421 --> 29:58.536
I should go change.

30:01.008 --> 30:04.296
U Love don't satisfy me J‘J‘

30:04.512 --> 30:08.926
J'J' 'Cause I'm leaving
with a smile on my face J‘J‘

30:09.767 --> 30:13.806
N You know I ain't that easy J‘J‘

30:14.021 --> 30:16.888
J‘J‘ Sometimes it's just so hard J‘J‘

